              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          
          <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3">
            <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle me-2"></i> <strong>Important:</strong> Always consult with your healthcare provider before starting a new exercise program, especially during pregnancy or if you have any health conditions.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Exercise and Menstrual Cycle</h5>
          
          <p>Your menstrual cycle can influence your energy levels, strength, endurance, and recovery. Understanding how to work with your cycle rather than against it can optimize your fitness results.</p>
          
          <div class="table-responsive mb-4">
            <table class="table table-bordered">
              <thead class="table-light">
                <tr>
                  <th>Cycle Phase</th>
                  <th>Hormonal State</th>
                  <th>Energy & Performance</th>
                  <th>Workout Recommendations</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Follicular Phase</strong><br>(Days 1-14, starts with period)</td>
                  <td>Rising estrogen</td>
                  <td>Energy gradually increases; good muscle recovery; higher pain tolerance</td>
                  <td>
                    <ul class="mb-0">
                      <li>Progressive strength training</li>
                      <li>HIIT workouts</li>
                      <li>Try new challenging activities</li>
                    </ul>
                  </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Ovulation</strong><br>(Around day 14)</td>
                  <td>Peak estrogen, rising testosterone</td>
                  <td>Energy and strength peak; highest power output potential</td>
                  <td>
                    <ul class="mb-0">
                      <li>High-intensity workouts</li>
                      <li>Strength training with heavier weights</li>
                      <li>Sports performance</li>
                    </ul>
                  </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Luteal Phase</strong><br>(Days 15-28)</td>
                  <td>Rising progesterone, falling estrogen</td>
                  <td>Energy decreases; increased core temperature; potential water retention; slower recovery</td>
                  <td>
                    <ul class="mb-0">
                      <li>Lower intensity steady-state cardio</li>
                      <li>Yoga and flexibility work</li>
                      <li>Light to moderate strength training</li>
                      <li>Focus on form and technique</li>
                    </ul>
                  </td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          
          <div class="alert alert-info">
            <i class="fas fa-info-circle me-2"></i> <strong>Note:</strong> These are general guidelines. Every woman's experience is unique, and factors like sleep, stress, and nutrition also play significant roles in energy levels and performance.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    
